Based on comments raised during the Planning Board hearing on October 16, 2013, McMahon
Associates has conducted additional traffic review and analysis for the proposed Cumberland
Farms project in North Grafton, MA. The following information is included in this memo based
on the comments from board members and neighboring residents:
Updated capacity analysis reflecting the site access modifications
Supplemental review of traffic data on Amherst Street
This memorandum documents the project modifications, additional data collection and
supplemental analysis which is intended to append the original Traffic Impact Study submitted
in August 2013 for the proposed project.
The Planning Board requested that that traffic study verify compliance with the Town of
Grafton Zoning Bylaws. Section 8 (Traffic Control) of the zoning bylaws outlines the objectives
and requirements of traffic studies conducted within in the Town. Based on a review of the
Traffic Control Bylaws, specifically Section 8.2 – Traffic Study Required, additional information
is contained within this memorandum to insure that the requirements of Section 8.2 have been
met. Specifically, additional trip generation estimates for the proposed Cumberland Farms
during an off peak hour were evaluated and are discussed subsequently in this memorandum.
In response to comments from the planning board and nearby residents, access to the project
site has been modified. At the request of Amherst Street residents, the Amherst Street driveway
(which exists on the site today) has been removed. Therefore, patrons will only be able to access
the site from Worcester Street and Williams Road. Additionally, at the request of the Planning
Board, the Worcester Street driveway closest to Williams Road has also been removed and all of
the access to and from Worcester Street will occur through a single driveway. An updated site
plan showing the revised driveway configuration has been submitted to the Town for review.
As a result of the proposed reconfiguration to the project site access, the capacity analysis of the
study area intersections was updated. The change in access to the project site results in a
modified distribution of project trips onto the study area roadways and project site driveways.
While the overall pattern of arrival and departure is expected to be the same as what was
presented in the Traffic Impact Study, individual movements at each of the site driveways is
expected to change with the new access configuration. The updated 2018 Build traffic volumes
for the weekday morning and weekday afternoon peak hours are depicted in schematics

As seen in the table above, each of the study area intersections are expected to operate at the
same level-of-service under the new proposed site plan as under the previously proposed site
plan configuration. The northbound site driveway movement exiting onto Worcester Street is
shown to incur additional delay with the closure of the second Worcester Street driveway, but
the capacity analysis indicates that the Worcester Street driveway is expected to operate well
under capacity. The northbound Williams Road approach is shown to operate with slightly
more vehicle delay with the proposed site plan changes, but is shown to continue to operate at
the same level-of-service under the 2018 No Build conditions.

To meet each of the traffic study requirements outlined in Section 8.2 of the Grafton Zoning
Bylaws, additional trip generation analysis was conducted for a “typical one hour not in the
peak period.” In order to generate an off peak number of trips expected to access the project
site, the daily traffic volume data collected on Worcester Street was reviewed. Due to the pass-
by nature of the project, it can be expected that the trip generation of the project site will
fluctuate with the hourly traffic along Worcester Street. The typical off peak hour was
identified as 12:00PM to 1:00PM. Based on the hourly distribution of traffic of Worcester Street,
the following trip generation was estimated for the off peak hour.

As shown in Table 3, the proposed Cumberland Farms is estimated generate approximately 56
“new” vehicle trips (28 entering vehicles and 28 exiting vehicles) during the 12:00PM to 1:00 PM
midday peak hour. With lower traffic volumes on Worcester Street and fewer vehicles
generated by the proposed project during the off peak hour, the project is not expected to have a
noticeable impact on traffic operations during the off peak time periods.
In order to compare the expected Cumberland Farms off peak trip generation to previous land
uses on site, the hourly distribution of trips generated by a supermarket and retail development
were reviewed. Based on hourly distribution data published by ITE for LUC 820 (Shopping
Center) the previous supermarket/retail land use is estimated to have generated approximately
200 vehicle trips (110 entering vehicles and 90 exiting vehicles) during the 12:00 to 1:00 hour.
Therefore, the number of trips expected to be generated by the proposed Cumberland Farms
project is shown to be less than the number of trips generated by a supermarket and mixed
retail land use during a midday off peak hour.
As a follow-up to the previous traffic impact study, McMahon has conducted further review of
the existing traffic along Amherst Street. In order to obtain a better understanding of traffic
patterns along Amherst Street, additional data was collected and analyzed within the
neighborhood. Traffic data was collected via an automatic traffic recorder (ATR) and manual
turning movement counts on Thursday, November 14, 2013. The ATR collected data for a 24-
hour period including traffic volume data and speed data on Amherst Street just west of the
project site. Manual turning movement counts were conducted at the intersection of Deernolm
Street and Harvard Street during the weekday morning (7:00 AM to 9:00 AM) and weekday
afternoon (4:00 PM to 6:00 PM) peak periods. Below is a discussion of the supplemental traffic
data collected within the adjacent residential neighborhood.
Hourly traffic volumes were collected for a 24-hour period utilizing an ATR on Amherst Street
located just west of the project site. The key traffic volume information based on the ATR data
Table 4 summarizes the weekday morning and weekday afternoon peak hour traffic volumes
recorded during the 24 hour count period on Thursday November 14, 2013. The average daily
traffic volume collected by the ATR is approximately 390 vehicles (160 eastbound and 230
westbound). As seen in the table, the overall weekday morning peak hour (total volumes in the
eastbound and westbound direction) is shown to occur from 6:30 AM to 7:30 AM and the

volumes along Amherst Street appear to remain fairly constant throughout the day (from 6:00
The turning movement counts at the intersection of Deernolm Street and Harvard Street were
used to better understand how local travel patterns affected Amherst Street. The peak hour on
Amherst Street based on the ATR data was recorded from 4:45 PM to 5:45 PM. The
corresponding turning movement count data indicated that during that peak hour, 13 vehicles
traveled from Deernolm Street to Harvard Street and 10 vehicles traveled from Harvard Street
toward Deernolm Street. Although the exact origin and destination of the vehicles traveling
between Deernolm Street and Harvard Street is unknown, these vehicles could be utilizing
Amherst Street as a connection between Deernolm Street and Williams Road. As a point of
comparison, a review of the traffic volumes traveling on Deernolm Street shows that greater
than 95% of vehicles continue past Harvard Street during both the weekday morning and
weekday afternoon peak periods. This existing travel pattern indicates that although a small
portion of vehicles may be utilizing Amherst Street as a connection between Deernolm Street
and Williams Road, the vast majority of vehicles traveling between Worcester Street and
Deernolm Street choose to stay on Deernolm Street instead of using Amherst Street.
The proposed Cumberland Farms project is not expected to alter existing traffic patterns in the
area as the majority of trips to the project site will be drawn from traffic already traveling past
the site. Therefore, Cumberland Farms patrons are not expected to use Amherst Street unless
they are a resident of that immediate area. As documented in the traffic study a small number
of vehicles are shown to access the project site to/from Amherst Street. These trips were
vehicles shown to already be accessing the existing site via Amherst Street and were assumed to
be residents of the neighborhood. Due to the high volumes on Worcester Street and the
predominately pass-by nature of Cumberland Farms, the number of vehicles accessing Amherst
Street from the project site is not expected to increase.
